03:04.269 --> 03:06.062
BEN: <i>Where the hell are we, Nell?</i>

03:06.271 --> 03:07.772
NELL: (CHUCKLING)
<i>Ready for a deer to jump out.</i>

03:07.939 --> 03:09.107
BEN: <i>This makes no sense.</i>

03:09.274 --> 03:11.943
<i>Who lives out here?</i> (STUTTERING)
<i>How long has she been out here?</i>

03:12.443 --> 03:13.611
NELL: I don't know. Six years, I guess.

03:13.778 --> 03:16.406
Six years?
She hasn't run a campaign in six years?

03:17.365 --> 03:19.242
You know she's lost
her last four elections.

03:19.450 --> 03:21.286
And there's the haphephobia.

03:21.536 --> 03:22.787
- The what?
- (NELL CHUCKLES)

03:23.288 --> 03:24.622
- Don't touch her.
- Oh.

03:24.873 --> 03:26.708
She doesn't like to be touched.

03:27.750 --> 03:29.210
- Well, you said you wanted different.
- (BOTH LAUGHING)

03:29.419 --> 03:31.796
- No, I said "unconventional," but...
- Oh.

03:32.297 --> 03:34.257
I mean, this is a presidential campaign.

03:34.924 --> 03:36.551
Ever heard of a disposable?

03:37.802 --> 03:39.888
No, what's a disposable?

03:40.096 --> 03:43.975
It's what the CIA call an agent
who's expendable and deniable.

03:44.893 --> 03:47.103
She has no kids, no family, no life.

03:47.312 --> 03:50.231
I've seen her take a dead horse
and bring in a landslide.

03:51.316 --> 03:54.944
- Hmm.
- So, if she turns this thing around,

03:55.153 --> 03:57.280
<i>well, we did it together.</i>

03:57.989 --> 03:59.324
<i>And if she messes it up,</i>

03:59.574 --> 04:02.285
(INHALES) <i>that'll be Calamity Jane.</i>

04:11.502 --> 04:12.921
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

04:14.088 --> 04:16.673
BEN: <i>It's a presidential campaign
in South America, Jane.</i>

04:16.925 --> 04:18.968
<i>Bolivia. Very interesting.</i>

04:19.177 --> 04:22.472
<i>Uh, economy in real trouble,
fragile democracy.</i>

04:22.680 --> 04:23.806
It's challenging.

04:24.015 --> 04:26.017
<i>Our main opposition is Victor Rivera.</i>

04:26.184 --> 04:28.603
He's a deputy in
the lower house of Congress,

04:28.811 --> 04:30.188
representing Potosi.

04:31.439 --> 04:34.817
He's an opportunist. He's a populist,

04:35.026 --> 04:37.654
and, well, he's... He's leading the field.

04:37.862 --> 04:39.864
- I like that hair.
- (LAUGHS)

04:40.698 --> 04:43.868
Now, our candidate is Pedro Castillo.

04:44.035 --> 04:45.662
Born in Bolivia, raised in America.

04:45.995 --> 04:48.873
He was actually elected
president 15 years ago.

04:49.123 --> 04:51.209
Privatized some industries,

04:51.376 --> 04:53.044
and wasn't a popular move for him.

04:53.294 --> 04:56.214
Mmm. So it was a gringo
stickin' it to the Indians.

04:56.464 --> 04:58.049
- Right?
- Right.

04:58.299 --> 05:00.385
- NELL: <i>Moving on.</i>
- How far are you behind?

05:02.053 --> 05:03.221
Twenty-eight points.

05:03.513 --> 05:05.056
(LAUGHS)

05:06.474 --> 05:08.851
Where you gonna find someone
to take on that shit basket?

05:09.560 --> 05:10.728
NELL: <i>Hey, Jane.</i>
JANE: Yeah?

05:10.979 --> 05:12.647
<i>Did you make this?</i>

05:13.564 --> 05:15.066
- This, uh, arts and crafts kind of thing?
- JANE: Yeah.

05:15.316 --> 05:16.985
Yep. It's a medicine bowl.

05:17.193 --> 05:19.195
It's based on a Mohawk design.

05:19.404 --> 05:22.907
This whole... This whole area
was, uh... Was Native territory.

05:23.157 --> 05:24.325
Take one.

05:24.534 --> 05:25.743
They have protective powers.

05:25.910 --> 05:27.912
It's supposed to
ward off the evil spirits.

05:28.871 --> 05:30.581
Most people use 'em for fruit.

05:31.374 --> 05:32.417
That's, um...

05:32.750 --> 05:34.585
Let me have the bowl.

05:40.425 --> 05:42.218
Well, this is quite a setup.

05:42.427 --> 05:44.554
I quit smoking, Nell. Can you believe it?

05:44.762 --> 05:46.014
NELL: <i>Ooh. Wow.</i>

05:46.681 --> 05:49.934
Haven't had a drink in three...
Three years.

05:50.226 --> 05:51.602
- NELL: <i>Oh.</i>
- I sleep nights.

05:51.853 --> 05:53.938
Some days, I can almost
look myself in the eye.

05:55.398 --> 05:56.524
You're happy?

05:56.733 --> 05:59.235
Oh, I'm better than happy. I am calm.

05:59.444 --> 06:00.570
You're a fighter, Jane.

06:00.778 --> 06:02.780
Can you look me in the eye
and tell me you don't miss it?

06:03.031 --> 06:04.032
Don't miss what?

06:04.365 --> 06:06.405
Candidates who can't think
unless we think for them?

06:07.535 --> 06:08.703
<i>No, ma'am. No.</i>

06:09.078 --> 06:10.705
You know what it did to me,
Nell, that whole world.

06:10.913 --> 06:12.457
- NELL: <i>Oh, blah, blah, blah.</i>
- It's not good for me. Okay.

06:12.623 --> 06:14.292
Yeah, well, they're paying very well.

06:14.459 --> 06:15.585
I'm sure they are.

06:15.793 --> 06:16.961
<i>I know you're struggling.</i>

06:17.128 --> 06:19.589
I mean, we're talking
a couple of months in La Paz.

06:19.797 --> 06:22.216
Oh, well, I get altitude sickness.

06:22.425 --> 06:24.093
- Oh, yeah? Well, you live on a mountain.
- Yeah.

06:24.302 --> 06:26.429
No, ma'am. I live between mountains.

06:26.971 --> 06:28.139
(DRY CHUCKLE)

06:35.063 --> 06:37.103
I know. I saw it.
Remember, I said he had good hair?

06:37.356 --> 06:39.817
Mmm-hmm. Look behind the hair.

06:40.485 --> 06:43.780
<i>There's one detail that Ben
neglected to mention.</i>

06:43.988 --> 06:46.824
The opposition has hired
their own American.

06:49.744 --> 06:50.995
<i>Pat Candy.</i>

06:55.917 --> 06:57.668
(SOFTLY) God, you guys are amazing.

06:57.919 --> 06:59.837
Amazing. Unbelievable.

07:00.088 --> 07:01.923
- What? Oh, come on.
- (JANE SCOFFS)

07:02.423 --> 07:04.592
He didn't beat you. You beat yourself.

07:04.842 --> 07:06.844
<i>And I'm giving you
another shot at the title.</i>

07:07.011 --> 07:08.846
- (SIGHS)
<i>- Light the fire, honey.</i>

07:09.680 --> 07:11.265
<i>You wanna go out? Go out.</i>

07:11.516 --> 07:12.683
<i>But go out a winner.</i>

07:12.934 --> 07:14.435
(SOFTLY) Damn it, Nell.

07:15.686 --> 07:18.022
NELL: <i>Castillo is a self-made millionaire.</i>

07:18.272 --> 07:20.191
<i>He's known as a conservative senator</i>

07:20.358 --> 07:21.859
<i>and a voice for globalization.</i>

07:22.026 --> 07:24.529
<i>Sure, there were some problems
the last time he was president,</i>

07:24.779 --> 07:28.366
<i>but he is back with a new,
positive attitude.</i>

07:28.616 --> 07:30.536
Just keep that fucking
hippopotamus away from me.

07:30.701 --> 07:32.370
- No problem.
- Okay.

07:33.204 --> 07:35.289
BUCKLEY:
It's all about extremes in Bolivia.

07:35.540 --> 07:38.209
It's the highest,
most isolated country in South America.

07:38.626 --> 07:40.211
You know, you got a wealthy urban elite

07:40.461 --> 07:43.101
who have been dominating
political and economic life for centuries,

07:43.214 --> 07:45.383
but the vast majority of
the population are dirt poor.

07:45.633 --> 07:47.385
<i>Now, they've had decades
of militaryjuntas,</i>

07:47.635 --> 07:49.470
<i>bloody coups, tanks on the street.</i>

07:49.720 --> 07:51.305
<i>I mean, it's no joke down there.</i>

07:51.556 --> 07:54.559
(IN SPANISH) <i>During your presidency,</i>
<i>there was a lot of social unrest.</i>

07:54.809 --> 07:58.563
So if you could go back in time,
what would you change?

07:59.188 --> 08:00.481
(CHUCKLES)

08:01.149 --> 08:02.567
BUCKLEY: <i>Is there something
wrong with her?</i>

08:02.817 --> 08:04.068
- NELL: <i>You okay, Jane?</i>
- Okay, so what is it?

08:04.318 --> 08:05.653
What did... What did he do?

08:05.903 --> 08:09.907
<i>Try and think. Perhaps all the people
who died during the protests?</i>

08:10.158 --> 08:12.410
Yes, I... I don't know.

08:12.827 --> 08:14.162
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

08:16.873 --> 08:18.499
AUDIENCE: Aww!

08:24.380 --> 08:25.423
<i>Hola.</i>

08:25.923 --> 08:28.593
NELL:...close together.
I'm just trying to get off the damn plane.

08:28.843 --> 08:30.178
Hi, thank you. Nice to see you.

08:30.428 --> 08:31.548
BEN: Looking sharp, Buckley.

08:32.929 --> 08:34.015
NELL: <i>Oh!</i>
BEN: <i>You okay?</i>

08:34.265 --> 08:35.600
Honey, honey, honey. Easy, easy.

08:35.850 --> 08:37.090
Probably the altitude sickness.

08:37.268 --> 08:39.437
We're so high up here,
you get low partial pressure of oxygen.

08:39.687 --> 08:40.938
Very common with the visitors.

08:41.188 --> 08:42.607
NELL: <i>She can't breathe.</i>
BUCKLEY: <i>She'll be all right.</i>

08:42.773 --> 08:44.275
Tell us more about our candidate.

08:44.442 --> 08:46.611
Well, Castillo's carrying
a lot of history,

08:46.861 --> 08:48.362
a lot of bad associations.

08:48.613 --> 08:50.114
So the job here, basically,

08:50.364 --> 08:52.783
is to take a candidate that
the electorate doesn't like,

08:53.034 --> 08:55.953
rebrand him, and then
sell him, sell him, sell him.

08:56.204 --> 08:57.955
Shouldn't be too difficult.

08:58.623 --> 08:59.790
<i>Look at those camels.</i>

09:00.041 --> 09:01.876
NELL: <i>They're not camels.
They're, um, llamas.</i>

09:02.126 --> 09:03.726
BUCKLEY: <i>Looks a lot like a camel to me.</i>

09:03.794 --> 09:04.795
BEN: <i>They are in the camel family.</i>

09:04.962 --> 09:07.381
<i>Llamas, alpacas, camels,
they're in the same family.</i>

09:07.632 --> 09:08.466
BUCKLEY: <i>Yeah,
those are baby hairy camels.</i>

09:08.716 --> 09:09.634
NELL: Can I put my bag here? It's okay?

09:09.884 --> 09:11.135
Can we just go, please?

09:11.385 --> 09:13.804
NELL: (STAMMERS) <i>Yeah, but do you</i>
<i>want, uh... Can you open your window?</i>

09:13.971 --> 09:15.806
- I want you to not speak for a second.
- NELL: <i>All right. Okay.</i>

09:16.057 --> 09:17.308
Sir? Uh, a little heat, please?

09:17.934 --> 09:19.268
(HORNS HONKING)

09:22.980 --> 09:24.649
(PROTESTORS CHANTING)

09:25.983 --> 09:28.402
(MAN SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY
ON LOUDSPEAKER)

09:31.906 --> 09:34.742
Ben, how do you pronounce these, uh,
indigenous, uh, people?

09:34.992 --> 09:36.160
- The... Yes.
- The Quechua?

09:36.410 --> 09:38.329
- Aymara. Guarani.
- Guarani.

09:38.579 --> 09:41.415
Constantly protesting.
They're pretty much the majority here.

09:41.666 --> 09:45.920
I mean, imagine... Imagine there was
200 million Apache back home.

09:46.170 --> 09:48.422
- (JANE GROANING)
- Gives you some kind of idea.

09:48.673 --> 09:49.673
Excuse me?

09:49.840 --> 09:51.175
(CHANTING CONTINUES)

09:51.509 --> 09:52.760
(YELLING IN SPANISH)

09:57.014 --> 09:59.350
BUCKLEY: <i>Please call him "Senator."</i>
NELL: <i>"Senator"?</i>

09:59.600 --> 10:00.685
BUCKLEY: <i>That's what's most respectful.</i>

10:00.935 --> 10:03.437
NELL: And are we
trying the <i>buenos días</i> thing?

10:03.854 --> 10:04.939
BUCKLEY: Um, you know, I wouldn't.

10:05.189 --> 10:07.858
Just keep it very American.
Pardon me, Jane.

10:08.025 --> 10:11.529
The aide always introduces you,
so let's just smile and shake hands.

10:11.779 --> 10:13.531
Yeah. Don't salute or anything like that.

10:13.781 --> 10:15.141
NELL: I'm not gonna salute anyone.

10:15.283 --> 10:17.159
BEN: <i>Buenos... Buenos días.</i>
NELL: <i>Buenos días.</i>

10:22.957 --> 10:23.958
Hugo. Ben Sawyer.

10:24.208 --> 10:26.210
- Ben Sawyer. Nice to finally meet you.
- This is my team.

10:26.460 --> 10:27.461
- Hugo Barco.
- Richard Buckley.

10:27.712 --> 10:28.713
- Nice to meet you.
- Ben.

10:28.879 --> 10:30.548
- Nice meeting you.
- Nell Talby. Such a pleasure.

10:30.715 --> 10:32.883
- (SUITCASE CLANGS)
- (JANE CLEARS THROAT)

10:33.301 --> 10:35.136
- NELL: You okay there?
- This is our, uh, specialist,

10:35.386 --> 10:36.387
- Jane Bodine.
- Are you okay?

10:36.554 --> 10:38.234
Jane Bodine. Hugo Barco. Nice to meet you.

10:38.472 --> 10:39.672
Senator Castillo, Jane Bodine.

10:39.807 --> 10:40.975
- CASTILLO: Nice to meet you.
- Nice to meet you.

10:41.225 --> 10:42.560
HUGO: Have a seat.

10:44.061 --> 10:46.397
We read the report. It was depressing.

10:46.647 --> 10:48.399
<i>So, what's the biopsy?</i>

10:48.649 --> 10:49.734
Is it... Is it terminal?

10:49.900 --> 10:52.236
Well, if we thought that, we wouldn't have
come all the way here, right?

10:52.403 --> 10:54.083
<i>We think you could win
this thing, Senator.</i>

10:54.322 --> 10:56.741
<i>What we'd like to do is
start with some focus groups,</i>

10:56.907 --> 10:59.577
<i>get an idea of what people
are thinking about you, get...</i>

11:00.077 --> 11:01.357
(SOFTLY) Keep going. Keep going.

11:01.412 --> 11:03.247
Really, really, really get people in here.

11:03.497 --> 11:04.915
<i>You know, go out to the streets,</i>

11:05.082 --> 11:08.169
<i>listen to what the people have
to say, and tell you. Okay?</i>

11:08.419 --> 11:09.587
<i>We are the conduit.</i>

11:09.754 --> 11:14.091
We're the syringe that injects
the people's voice into your campaign.

11:14.342 --> 11:16.177
Meanwhile, I'll be headin' up, uh, media.

11:16.427 --> 11:18.929
Online awareness, outreach,
TV ads, and so forth.

11:19.096 --> 11:20.181
BEN: <i>Nell?</i>

11:20.431 --> 11:23.768
NELL: What we can say now for sure
is that the opposition is going

11:24.018 --> 11:27.271
to play you as the oligarch. The elitist.

11:27.521 --> 11:30.274
So, what we're going to do is invert that.

11:30.441 --> 11:31.776
We're gonna show the people that,

11:32.026 --> 11:35.112
in fact, you are not
the stooge of the corporation,

11:35.279 --> 11:36.364
but one of them.

11:36.614 --> 11:40.618
We want to show the people
the warm, likable Castillo.

11:40.868 --> 11:42.953
BEN: And that's why we've brought
our strategist in,

11:43.204 --> 11:44.288
the great Jane Bodine,

11:44.455 --> 11:46.957
to give us some insight
on how we'd do that.

11:49.293 --> 11:52.463
Uh, Jane, you wanna share
some of your, uh, ideas on how we would...

11:53.464 --> 11:55.824
- I mean, there are many ways. We can...
- Uh... Yeah. Um...

11:55.883 --> 11:57.218
- You can see here...
- Hold on, hold on, just...

11:57.468 --> 11:58.803
JANE: <i>Just a second.</i>

11:59.053 --> 12:02.640
When we were on the plane,
she said to me, uh, you know,

12:02.807 --> 12:05.643
"Shakespeare once said,
'If you take a great man...

12:05.893 --> 12:08.213
"'If you take a great man
and cut off one of his hands..."'

12:08.270 --> 12:09.605
She is okay? Would you like some water?

12:09.814 --> 12:12.274
(GAGGING) Okay. I need to, um...

12:12.608 --> 12:14.068
I need... I'll be right...

12:14.318 --> 12:15.319
(EXHALES)

12:15.569 --> 12:17.655
She's not...
It's... It's the altitude sickness.

12:17.905 --> 12:19.156
<i>- Soroche.</i>
- BEN: <i>Soroche,</i> yes.

12:19.407 --> 12:21.247
- HUGO: Let's go on.
- So let's continue. Um...

12:21.575 --> 12:22.993
(VOMITING)

12:23.577 --> 12:24.829
Uh...

12:27.581 --> 12:28.916
(CHUCKLING)

12:29.125 --> 12:30.918
NELL: How 'bout some water?
JANE: Mmm-mmm.

12:31.585 --> 12:33.337
I think you should hold off
on those chips a little bit, honey.

12:33.587 --> 12:35.339
- He's not a winner.
- What?

12:35.589 --> 12:37.133
Castillo. He is not a winner.

12:37.341 --> 12:39.427
You can smell a winner,
same as me, and he's not one.

12:39.635 --> 12:40.803
Oh. Well, not yet.

12:41.011 --> 12:43.347
But that's why we're here. (CHUCKLES)

12:43.764 --> 12:45.099
(SIGHING)

13:13.002 --> 13:14.295
(FLY BUZZING)

13:23.012 --> 13:24.305
(BUZZING CONTINUES)

13:31.687 --> 13:34.190
BUCKLEY: <i>It's gotta feel like
you've lost everything,</i>

13:34.398 --> 13:35.983
<i>that you have nothing more to live for.</i>

13:36.192 --> 13:38.402
And we find you,
right in the guts of the favelas,

13:38.652 --> 13:41.822
among the disenfranchised
and hopeless. Okay?

13:42.031 --> 13:44.408
- Does she speak English? No?
- Uh, no.

13:44.658 --> 13:48.662
Tell the little girl that she stands
in front of the slum thing there.

13:48.996 --> 13:50.581
- (TRANSLATING INTO SPANISH)
- And the effect is all fake.

13:50.831 --> 13:52.833
She falls backwards through the sky.

13:53.042 --> 13:54.376
Castillo catches her.

13:55.002 --> 13:56.170
Okay? Okay.

13:56.378 --> 13:58.088
(GIRL SPEAKING SPANISH)

13:59.507 --> 14:01.217
What? What'd she say?

14:01.425 --> 14:04.011
She say that she doesn't think
that he will catching her.

14:04.220 --> 14:05.429
He's gonna... He'll catch you.

14:05.679 --> 14:07.723
Why would... Why would he not catch you?

14:08.265 --> 14:10.184
(SNAPS FINGERS)
Why would he not catch you?

14:10.434 --> 14:11.994
- (CRYING)
- Oh, my God. Let's go again!

14:12.019 --> 14:14.104
Your secret weapon.
So secret I forgot she was there.

14:14.355 --> 14:15.606
- Suck a duck, Hugo.
- HUGO: <i>You suck a duck.</i>

14:15.856 --> 14:16.857
BEN: <i>Why'd you make the little girl cry?</i>

14:17.066 --> 14:18.275
I can't work under these conditions.

14:18.442 --> 14:20.444
You know? And what is she doing?

14:20.694 --> 14:21.695
<i>I mean, I've hardly even seen her.</i>

14:21.904 --> 14:23.948
She shows up and she's sunbathing? Really?

14:24.198 --> 14:26.598
Rich is right. This what Castillo
paid for? This is strategy?

14:26.700 --> 14:29.370
- This looks unprofessional.
- She hasn't lit the fire, Ben.

14:29.578 --> 14:31.789
- Well, somebody light the fire, then.
- Would you just give her a beat?

14:32.039 --> 14:33.519
- Light a fire.
- (YELLING IN SPANISH)

14:34.041 --> 14:35.960
- What?
- She don't go do it, mister.

14:36.210 --> 14:37.628
What do you mean?
No, he's going to catch her.

14:37.878 --> 14:38.879
- I promise you.
- (YELLING IN SPANISH)

14:39.129 --> 14:40.589
And then she can have some candy.

14:40.798 --> 14:42.800
<i>- Tranquilo,</i> is that...
- Yeah, that's it.

14:43.050 --> 14:44.468
<i>Tranquilo.</i>

14:44.718 --> 14:46.804
We're going to shoot
the commercial, <i>por favor.</i>

14:47.054 --> 14:48.097
That was good.

14:48.430 --> 14:49.590
(SPEAKING SPANISH) <i>I see you!</i>

14:51.267 --> 14:52.268
<i>I've got you!</i>

14:58.440 --> 15:00.734
<i>Our proposal will give Bolivia
a brighter future.</i>

15:00.943 --> 15:02.194
NELL: Oh, my God.

15:02.403 --> 15:04.196
(IN SPANISH) <i>I know that it will be hard,</i>

15:04.613 --> 15:07.741
<i>but together we will triumph.</i>

15:09.076 --> 15:10.869
(SPANISH JINGLE PLAYING)

15:14.290 --> 15:18.377
TRANSLATOR: <i>Uh-huh. They have two people
that are talking against him.</i>

15:18.586 --> 15:21.547
They're saying that he's not trustworthy,

15:21.755 --> 15:22.798
he's not reliable.

15:23.048 --> 15:25.926
(IN SPANISH) His commercial is horrible.
It's technically embarrassing.

15:26.302 --> 15:29.054
Basically, he doesn't relate
to the Bolivian people.

15:29.263 --> 15:31.307
In my opinion,
it's totally wrong.

15:31.932 --> 15:34.059
- It is unanimous, yes.
- So, are we hearing this?

15:34.268 --> 15:36.645
Unanimous, finding it a joke, the...
The floating down.

15:36.895 --> 15:37.980
BUCKLEY: Well, I had
to make it look Bolivian,

15:38.230 --> 15:39.940
and like I said,
we had a low budget on the effects.

15:40.190 --> 15:41.191
Comical.

15:41.442 --> 15:44.642
BEN: You have to do something to make this
guy seem more likable to human beings.

15:44.778 --> 15:46.113
BUCKLEY: <i>It's his smile.</i>

15:46.322 --> 15:47.740
<i>- His smile is weird. It's off.</i>
- Where is my strategist?

15:47.948 --> 15:50.492
- Come on, man.
- It's not happenin', you know?

15:50.743 --> 15:52.244
<i>It's like the Bush smile. The smirk.</i>

15:52.453 --> 15:53.912
BEN: <i>He won. Twice.</i>

15:54.121 --> 15:56.921
- Karl Rove had to beat that out of him.
- CASTILLO: <i>And my strategist?</i>

15:57.291 --> 15:59.418
Where is my strategist?

15:59.627 --> 16:03.005
- NELL: <i>She's not...</i>
- The commercial doesn't work, obviously.

16:04.006 --> 16:06.091
Falling out of the sky doesn't work.

16:06.300 --> 16:08.844
- My smile is obviously not good.
- BUCKLEY: Mmm-hmm.

16:09.428 --> 16:10.596
So where is she?

16:11.972 --> 16:14.308
I'm looking forward to hearing her plan,

16:14.516 --> 16:17.186
perhaps before the election is over.

16:22.650 --> 16:24.818
(SIGHS) What are you doin' out here?

16:25.027 --> 16:26.820
Oh, it's the nausea.

16:27.321 --> 16:29.698
I don't wanna keep vomiting
every time I see him.

16:29.948 --> 16:32.159
- Can't be good for his morale.
- (SCOFFS)

16:33.285 --> 16:35.496
- Um, we're strugglin'.
- Mmm-hmm.

16:35.704 --> 16:37.706
- Nothing's working.
- Nope.

16:38.540 --> 16:39.833
- That's it?
- Hmm.

16:40.042 --> 16:42.294
Because if you've got some
kind of trick up your sleeve,

16:42.503 --> 16:44.503
- now is the time to pull it out.
- (JANE CHUCKLES)

16:44.838 --> 16:47.508
This actually kinda matters, Jane.

16:48.300 --> 16:49.968
I mean, this country could go under.

16:50.177 --> 16:52.179
We're talkin' about
people's lives, you know?

16:52.971 --> 16:55.849
You don't think there's
something kinda odd about him?

16:56.058 --> 16:58.560
Sort of checked out?

16:59.687 --> 17:02.523
I think he's a client who's paying you
to be his strategist.

17:02.731 --> 17:03.982
Oh, okay.

17:04.191 --> 17:05.192
Do we have a problem?

17:05.401 --> 17:07.152
Because if we do, you need to tell me.

17:07.361 --> 17:10.196
If there's a problem, Ben,
I will tell you.

17:10.906 --> 17:13.867
(IN SPANISH) <i>It is unacceptable</i>
<i>that our natural resources</i>

17:14.201 --> 17:18.872
continue to be looted
and exploited illegally.

17:19.205 --> 17:22.000
This is something
I am determined to stop.

17:22.209 --> 17:23.919
They cannot keep
stealing from us.

17:24.294 --> 17:25.671
(APPLAUSE)

17:31.009 --> 17:33.429
(SPEAKING SPANISH) My priority is jobs,

17:33.762 --> 17:37.391
which I believe is
the priority of all Bolivians.

17:38.058 --> 17:41.520
Jobs, jobs, jobs.

17:42.062 --> 17:46.400
<i>Jobs building roads
and building schools,</i>

17:46.734 --> 17:49.236
<i>which the Bolivian people
desperately need.</i>

17:49.445 --> 17:50.445
(AUDIENCE CHEERING)

17:50.571 --> 17:52.614
<i>I'm sure that
my esteemed opponents</i>

17:52.865 --> 17:54.742
<i>could argue all night long...</i>

17:56.785 --> 17:58.537
CANDY: <i>There she is.</i>

17:59.079 --> 18:00.080
<i>Jane Bodine.</i>

18:00.456 --> 18:01.582
How are ya, honey?

18:05.711 --> 18:07.463
- Pat.
- So, what are you doin' here?

18:07.713 --> 18:09.590
I thought you retired
or gave up or somethin'.

18:10.048 --> 18:13.427
No, not retired. Working.

18:13.635 --> 18:15.554
Yeah. Okay.

18:15.763 --> 18:16.889
- Here lending a hand.
- Mmm.

18:17.097 --> 18:18.098
Nice.

18:18.307 --> 18:19.308
You?

18:19.725 --> 18:22.895
Same thing, yeah.
I'm just doin' a favor, you know?

18:23.103 --> 18:25.272
Yeah, but I'll probably be
going home tomorrow,

18:25.481 --> 18:26.815
so I won't stay around too long.

18:27.065 --> 18:28.901
- No? Yeah, me either.
- Mmm-mmm.

18:29.109 --> 18:31.403
- Probably gonna get outta here. Yeah.
- Mmm.

18:31.612 --> 18:32.988
But you good otherwise?

18:33.280 --> 18:34.615
CANDY: <i>Couldn't be better. Yeah.</i>
JANE: <i>Yeah?</i>

18:34.948 --> 18:38.786
- Enjoying this dog and pony show?
- I'm not one for crowds.

18:38.994 --> 18:41.622
- People suck, don't they?
- Yeah, sometimes.

18:41.955 --> 18:42.998
Yeah.

18:43.290 --> 18:45.501
You look tired.

18:45.751 --> 18:48.420
- You okay?
- I think so. I think I'm good. Why?

18:48.629 --> 18:50.756
I don't know. You just look a little beat.

18:51.089 --> 18:52.508
What do you think of Rivera?

18:52.758 --> 18:54.927
- I don't speak Spanish.
- Yeah, me either.

18:55.135 --> 18:56.375
- He looks good, though.
- Yeah.

18:56.512 --> 18:58.764
Yeah. Presidential timber.
How about your horse?

19:00.307 --> 19:02.100
Seems like a stuck-up
little asshole to me.

19:02.351 --> 19:03.977
Hmm? Hmm.

19:04.436 --> 19:08.315
Anyway, enjoy yourself
as much as you possibly can.

19:08.524 --> 19:10.776
- I will try.
- And, uh... Yeah.

19:11.276 --> 19:13.028
- So maybe later, huh?
- Maybe.

19:13.362 --> 19:14.696
- Yeah?
- Mmm-hmm.

19:14.988 --> 19:16.615
You know what I mean, right?

19:17.157 --> 19:18.200
I can only assume.

19:18.492 --> 19:20.869
- Yeah, honey. Okay. Bye.
- Yeah.

19:23.622 --> 19:24.832
Fuck!

19:26.291 --> 19:28.710
Fuck. Fuck!

19:31.004 --> 19:32.214
(APPLAUSE)

19:32.673 --> 19:34.049
♪ (FUNK MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

20:16.383 --> 20:17.718
(INAUDIBLE)

20:18.343 --> 20:19.803
(MUSIC DISTORTS)

20:23.724 --> 20:25.350
- (CROWD GASP)
- (CAMERAS CLICKING)

20:26.059 --> 20:27.102
NELL: <i>Oh, my God!</i>

20:30.147 --> 20:31.481
(YELLING IN SPANISH)

20:47.164 --> 20:48.957
(CAMERAS CONTINUE CLICKING)

21:01.386 --> 21:02.930
Well, you're kinda late.
I don't know if you've heard,

21:03.138 --> 21:05.098
- but we've pretty much gone belly up.
- Don't touch me.

21:05.307 --> 21:06.475
JANE: Are you guys drafting an apology?

21:06.725 --> 21:08.393
- Yeah.
- Uh, yeah. I... I don't know.

21:08.602 --> 21:10.402
Have any of you ever fought
against Mr. Candy?

21:10.604 --> 21:12.230
No, I know his reputation.
He's one of the best.

21:12.439 --> 21:13.440
Oh, yeah, well, it was him. It was him.

21:13.774 --> 21:15.067
The guy that threw the egg,
it was just a put-up job.

21:15.275 --> 21:16.902
- Whoa, whoa, what?
- JANE: <i>It was a put-up job.</i>

21:17.110 --> 21:18.320
<i>I know Candy. This is Sun Tzu.</i>

21:18.570 --> 21:20.890
"If your opponent is
of choleric temperament, provoke him."

21:21.073 --> 21:22.491
Do not send out an apology.

21:22.741 --> 21:23.742
Jane, I don't know if you missed it,

21:23.951 --> 21:26.631
- but Castillo hit someone in the face.
- Okay, it was self-defense.

21:26.787 --> 21:28.246
- He was attacked.
- It was an egg.

21:28.455 --> 21:31.083
"Attack your enemy where he is unprepared.
Appear where you are unexpected."

21:31.291 --> 21:32.417
- It's Sun Tzu again.
- (SCOFFS) I know.

21:32.626 --> 21:34.346
I'm just not a big fan
of <i>Art of War</i> quotes.

21:34.503 --> 21:37.089
- Oh, yeah? Why... Why not?
- Because you can use them anywhere.

21:37.297 --> 21:38.857
And I don't think that modern democracy

21:38.924 --> 21:40.804
has anything to do with
ancient Chinese warfare.

21:40.926 --> 21:43.303
Yeah, well, no disrespect, Ben,
but that's why you're 30 points behind.

21:43.512 --> 21:45.639
Okay? And right now the enemy's
expecting you to apologize.

21:45.847 --> 21:47.975
Well, I don't think of the opposition
as the enemy, Calamity.

21:48.183 --> 21:49.351
Well, no disrespect, Ben,

21:49.601 --> 21:51.019
but that's another reason
you're 30 points behind.

21:51.269 --> 21:52.989
And the third reason
you're 30 points behind

21:53.021 --> 21:55.701
is 'cause you guys have Castillo
pretending to be somebody he's not.

21:55.941 --> 21:59.319
He's not a great actor.
Being warm isn't him, smiling isn't him,

21:59.528 --> 22:00.821
and apologizing isn't him.

22:01.029 --> 22:03.109
But punching someone
in the face, that... That's him?

22:03.281 --> 22:04.700
Yes, that's him.

22:04.950 --> 22:05.951
- Oh, come on, Jane.
- Yes. She has a point.

22:06.159 --> 22:07.577
Fine. For the sake of argument,

22:07.786 --> 22:10.247
Castillo is considered
arrogant, unapproachable,

22:10.455 --> 22:12.958
- and out of touch with people's lives.
- JANE: Mmm-hmm.

22:13.166 --> 22:15.043
So, what would you
have done differently, Jane?

22:15.293 --> 22:16.586
Well... (CRUNCHING)

22:16.795 --> 22:19.235
"A man's strengths flow from
the same well as his weaknesses."

22:19.464 --> 22:20.465
Okay.

22:20.841 --> 22:22.968
You don't change the man
to fit the narrative.

22:23.176 --> 22:25.012
You change the narrative to fit the man.

22:25.804 --> 22:27.806
- NELL: <i>That's excellent.</i>
- Thank you, Nell.

22:28.015 --> 22:29.215
How can a narrative fit a man?

22:29.307 --> 22:30.892
Just take it in a minute, will you?

22:31.143 --> 22:32.394
Exactly.

22:39.234 --> 22:40.861
"People forget what you say,

22:41.069 --> 22:43.071
"but they remember
how you make them feel."

22:43.363 --> 22:44.573
Warren Beatty.

22:45.157 --> 22:48.326
And right now you make people feel
like you're gonna shoot them.

22:48.827 --> 22:50.912
People don't like you. But that's okay.

22:51.580 --> 22:54.458
"Since love and fear can
hardly exist together,

22:54.666 --> 22:56.126
"if we must choose between them,

22:56.334 --> 22:59.755
"it is far safer to be feared than loved."

23:00.005 --> 23:02.174
That's Warren Beatty as well.
(LAUGHING)

23:03.341 --> 23:04.718
<i>No, it's not. It's Machiavelli.</i>

23:04.926 --> 23:06.344
Sorry. I was just totally kidding.

23:06.553 --> 23:08.597
Fear. Let's talk about fear.

23:09.514 --> 23:12.267
The most effective
political spot ever made,

23:12.517 --> 23:13.518
"Daisy."

23:13.852 --> 23:17.564
Pretty much won the election for Johnson,
and it was shown once.

23:18.023 --> 23:19.316
Basically, this ad suggested

23:19.524 --> 23:21.526
that if Goldwater got in
instead of Johnson,

23:21.735 --> 23:23.236
the crazy bastard would unleash

23:23.445 --> 23:25.947
a nuclear holocaust that would
just blow up the world.

23:26.198 --> 23:28.366
So now this became a choice between

23:28.575 --> 23:30.243
saving the world and dying.

23:30.452 --> 23:34.081
<i>You see, when voters are looking for hope,
they always go for the new guy.</i>

23:34.289 --> 23:35.749
But when they're scared,

23:36.792 --> 23:38.794
they look for a wartime leader.

23:39.211 --> 23:40.712
They look for a guy who,

23:40.921 --> 23:42.631
when you come at him with an egg,

23:42.881 --> 23:44.674
he doesn't have time for fun and games.

23:44.883 --> 23:48.053
No, he's gonna put you down,
and he's gonna punch you in the face!

23:48.303 --> 23:50.889
So let me tell you what our little movie
is gonna be about.

23:51.139 --> 23:56.353
Our story is Bolivia is facing
the worst period in its turbulent history.

23:56.561 --> 23:59.439
We are at a crossroads,
and Bolivians face a choice.

23:59.648 --> 24:01.691
They have Rivera, a man of no substance,

24:01.900 --> 24:04.653
a man of no experience,
an everyman opportunist,

24:04.903 --> 24:08.907
who will stand by and watch
as this nation falls apart,

24:09.116 --> 24:11.743
or they can choose Castillo.

24:12.244 --> 24:13.495
You might not like him.

24:13.745 --> 24:16.164
You might think
he's an arrogant son of a bitch.

24:16.414 --> 24:18.333
But he is a fighter.

24:18.583 --> 24:20.877
He has grit, he has experience,

24:21.086 --> 24:23.880
and he's got balls,
and he is the only choice.

24:24.089 --> 24:25.924
The only choice to save the day.

24:26.133 --> 24:27.592
These are the stakes.

24:27.801 --> 24:31.221
We are trying to save
people's lives, okay?

24:31.429 --> 24:33.682
But this is no longer an election.

24:35.851 --> 24:37.644
This is a crisis.

24:39.437 --> 24:40.939
And our brand,

24:42.107 --> 24:43.942
what we are selling,

24:46.945 --> 24:48.196
crisis.

24:49.823 --> 24:50.949
CASTILLO: Hmm.

24:51.616 --> 24:53.285
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

24:54.786 --> 24:56.329
If this phone rings, do not answer.

24:56.621 --> 24:59.457
Everything changes tonight,
and this is the tipping point.

24:59.666 --> 25:02.002
We have every single
major outlet in La Paz...

25:02.210 --> 25:03.930
- Right outside the door.
- All eyes on you.

25:03.962 --> 25:06.089
Do not apologize.

25:06.298 --> 25:08.216
But you do regret the incident.

25:08.466 --> 25:11.178
And you regret that it's drawn
the focus away from the issues

25:11.386 --> 25:13.586
- that we should be speaking about.
- (SPEAKING SPANISH)

25:13.680 --> 25:18.018
The struggle to save our country
from the social and economic crisis.

25:18.226 --> 25:19.352
- Crisis.
- Crisis.

25:23.648 --> 25:25.648
Man, can I bum one of these?
Can I... Can I take...

25:25.817 --> 25:27.819
<i>Gracias</i>. Just... (STAMMERS) Thank you.

25:28.486 --> 25:29.696
Mmm.

25:31.156 --> 25:32.490
(MOANS)

25:33.700 --> 25:35.535
<i>Fuck</i>. (COUGHING)

25:35.744 --> 25:37.996
Oh, my God. Is this a cigarette?

25:38.246 --> 25:39.331
<i>So bad for you.</i>

25:39.539 --> 25:41.166
Hey. Excuse me. <i>Hola.</i>

25:41.499 --> 25:43.501
- (STAMMERS) Do you speak English?
- Yes.

25:43.877 --> 25:46.677
Are you the guy that jumped in front
of, uh, Castillo after the debate?

25:46.880 --> 25:49.424
- Uh, yes.
- No, no, no. You're quick. You're quick.

25:49.841 --> 25:51.635
- What's your name again?
- Eduardo Camacho.

25:51.843 --> 25:54.443
- JANE: <i>Eduardo... That's a lot of name.</i>
- (SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

25:54.721 --> 25:58.141
Yes, whatever. Eddie, how about we just...
We'll call you Eddie. There you go.

25:58.350 --> 25:59.684
You're employee of the month.

25:59.893 --> 26:03.271
That's steak sauce. It's really good.
I bring it everywhere I go.

26:03.688 --> 26:05.565
That one says steaks,
but you can use it on all the meats.

26:05.857 --> 26:07.275
(CHUCKLES) This guy is George Bush?

26:08.193 --> 26:09.945
No, that's, um, Paul Newman, the actor.

26:10.195 --> 26:12.572
You know. Fast Eddie.
Fast Eddie, like you.

26:12.864 --> 26:14.532
- Keep it up, okay?
- (EDDIE CHUCKLES)

26:15.617 --> 26:17.494
And that alone is another fight.

26:17.702 --> 26:18.745
"Another fight"? Really?

26:18.954 --> 26:20.474
Just cut "another." "This is a fight."

26:20.622 --> 26:22.374
That's a fight that you will embrace.

26:22.666 --> 26:24.334
- (SPEAKING SPANISH)
- (KNOCKING ON GLASS)

26:24.542 --> 26:26.503
Gotta go. Take the jacket off
and roll up your...

26:26.711 --> 26:28.431
Uh, Ingrid,
you'll take that jacket, please.

26:28.546 --> 26:29.881
Senator, roll up your sleeves.

26:30.090 --> 26:33.802
(IN SPANISH) <i>Once again, indigenous</i>
<i>protestors paralyze the capital,</i>

26:34.094 --> 26:36.554
<i>demanding constitutional reforms</i>

26:36.763 --> 26:39.891
<i>that would give them
adequate representation.</i>

26:42.644 --> 26:44.271
(ALL APPLAUDING)

26:48.108 --> 26:49.734
(RALLY SPEAKER
SPEAKING SPANISH)

26:53.738 --> 26:54.990
(CAMERAS CLICKING)

27:29.607 --> 27:31.234
(DOG BARKING IN DISTANCE)

28:14.152 --> 28:16.321
JANE: <i>Candy moved
into the room opposite me.</i>

28:16.529 --> 28:19.115
Tryin' to get in my head.
Which is a mistake.

28:19.324 --> 28:21.244
My head being one place
you don't wanna get into.

28:21.326 --> 28:23.411
Jane, how many times have
you gone against Candy?

28:23.661 --> 28:25.080
Uh, three or four times.

28:25.872 --> 28:27.207
How many times has he beat you?

28:27.415 --> 28:29.167
Uh, three or four times.

28:29.834 --> 28:31.211
Don't make this personal, okay?

28:31.419 --> 28:33.505
It's just a job, Ben. It's just a job.

28:38.385 --> 28:40.345
Shirt sleeves rolled up, Senator.

28:42.847 --> 28:43.848
(SOFTLY) Senator.

28:44.474 --> 28:45.809
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

28:51.689 --> 28:54.275
- Thank you.
- Yeah, yeah. You're welcome.

28:54.734 --> 28:57.195
- I don't think we've met before.
- JANE: Almost up, Senator.

28:58.571 --> 29:00.281
Eduardo Camacho, sir.

29:02.283 --> 29:05.286
Actually, we met before, sir.

29:05.620 --> 29:10.041
A long time ago,
when, uh, they made you president.

29:10.250 --> 29:12.127
Plaza Murillo. I was there.

29:12.377 --> 29:13.377
- Ah.
- I came to see you.

29:13.545 --> 29:16.881
- You remember that?
- Yes, sir. I remember.

29:17.215 --> 29:20.260
I was very little,
and I couldn't see anything.

29:20.468 --> 29:22.762
And you came and you picked me up.

29:24.431 --> 29:26.433
That was a happy day.

29:28.893 --> 29:30.728
It will be again soon.

29:32.814 --> 29:34.816
No. Keep those for me, will you?

29:46.119 --> 29:47.787
(APPLAUSE)

29:52.917 --> 29:56.421
<i>And that's why I'm here today:
to say that we have a plan</i>

29:56.629 --> 29:59.090
to combat this crisis,

29:59.424 --> 30:01.342
to overcome this crisis.

30:01.634 --> 30:04.929
<i>That's why I'm asking
all of you to join me</i>

30:05.930 --> 30:07.098
in this fight.

30:07.807 --> 30:08.808
For Bolivia,

30:09.100 --> 30:10.268
with Castillo!

30:10.477 --> 30:11.895
(ALL CHEERING)

30:15.690 --> 30:17.400
And let me tell you, Bodine is right.

30:17.609 --> 30:19.152
The crisis message works.

30:19.360 --> 30:20.600
I can feel it with an audience.

30:20.695 --> 30:23.323
Maybe with the people here today,
but not with the working class.

30:23.531 --> 30:26.091
You say "crisis" to them,
they hear "tax raise" and we lose them.

30:26.201 --> 30:29.496
It absolutely kills me to say it,
but that's not a bad point.

30:29.704 --> 30:31.144
All right, we can't get comfortable.

30:31.206 --> 30:33.625
Don't forget agriculture and...
And key industry angles

30:33.833 --> 30:35.043
the other candidates are hitting hard.

30:35.293 --> 30:36.461
How do we attract votes from people

30:36.669 --> 30:38.379
who aren't gonna show up
to your urban support rallies?

30:38.630 --> 30:39.631
- Exactly.
- Look at me.

30:39.964 --> 30:42.050
We need to appeal to them
through advertising.

30:42.300 --> 30:43.801
So I have some storyboards
that I've sketched up

30:44.010 --> 30:45.011
that I wanna run through with you

30:45.220 --> 30:46.387
<i>- as soon as we get back to the office.</i>
- Senator.

30:46.638 --> 30:48.139
There you are. My cuff links.

30:48.348 --> 30:50.642
You know, I think you gave me luck today.

30:51.559 --> 30:53.186
What did you say your name is again?

30:54.145 --> 30:55.438
Eduardo Camacho.

30:55.647 --> 30:58.149
Eduardo Camacho. It's a pleasure.

30:58.900 --> 31:01.027
BUCKLEY: Sir, your car's downstairs.

31:03.655 --> 31:06.199
ASSISTANT: <i>I raise him from he was a baby.</i>

31:06.407 --> 31:07.408
Here we go again.

31:07.659 --> 31:09.786
I name him Marco after my father.

31:09.994 --> 31:12.154
He doesn't look anything like
he did in the photograph.

31:12.330 --> 31:15.041
He's a far more
beautiful creature in person.

31:15.250 --> 31:16.918
I mean, his posture's striking.

31:17.168 --> 31:18.753
He seems very affectionate, too.

31:19.087 --> 31:21.172
Excuse me. Can we get on
with the filmings?

31:21.381 --> 31:22.966
I have more important things to do.

31:23.174 --> 31:24.842
- BUCKLEY: Dude. Excuse me.
- Thank you.

31:25.176 --> 31:28.012
More important than harnessing
the sentiment of the working class?

31:28.221 --> 31:29.221
I don't think so.

31:29.347 --> 31:30.557
- BEN: <i>Sir, I'm sorry.</i>
- (LLAMA BRAYING)

31:30.765 --> 31:31.724
BEN: <i>Rich's process is to get...</i>
- Wow.

31:31.933 --> 31:33.173
More intimate with the animals.

31:33.351 --> 31:34.936
- But it's getting late.
- No, but once you see the animals...

31:35.186 --> 31:36.479
Just warming up
the llama for you, Senator.

31:36.688 --> 31:38.273
...you'll be more of
the collective creative process.

31:38.523 --> 31:41.234
Once we start shooting,
you'll see it'll move faster, so...

31:41.526 --> 31:42.527
BUCKLEY: Walk with me.

31:42.860 --> 31:44.404
Rich, why don't you show him
some of your shots?

31:44.696 --> 31:46.698
So, what I'm thinking
is that we open on his face.

31:46.906 --> 31:47.906
<i>Gracias.</i>

31:48.074 --> 31:50.743
Is that for the headache?
The Senator might...

31:50.952 --> 31:54.205
And then we do a slow dissolve
to you feeding the llama,

31:54.414 --> 31:57.500
and then you say, "Llamas supply..."

31:57.709 --> 32:01.546
"Llamas. They supply us with
meat, with wool, with milk.

32:01.754 --> 32:03.548
"With new scientific farming methods,

32:03.756 --> 32:07.010
"they can provide the key to
Bolivia's economic recovery.

32:07.218 --> 32:08.261
<i>"Key to jobs.</i>

32:08.469 --> 32:11.055
"For centuries, the llamas
led us through the mountains.

32:11.264 --> 32:14.392
"Now this animal
would lead us to prosperity."

32:14.601 --> 32:16.603
- No, that's good. I like it.
- That's good. Yeah, I like it, too.

32:16.811 --> 32:18.980
Uh, but you'll be saying that
walking towards camera,

32:19.230 --> 32:21.190
arms slightly away from
your hips for empowerment.

32:21.232 --> 32:22.150
- Yeah.
- And right down the barrel

32:22.358 --> 32:23.484
of the lens as you walk.

32:23.818 --> 32:25.653
(CLEARS THROAT)
Llamas. They will provide us

32:25.903 --> 32:28.781
with meat, with wool, with milk.

32:29.741 --> 32:32.160
- Huh? Is that good?
- More wrist twits, like a gorilla.

32:32.410 --> 32:33.490
(IMITATES CASTILLO) Llamas.

32:33.578 --> 32:34.662
- You must be kidding.
- No, serious.

32:34.912 --> 32:37.165
<i>- This is how we win elections.</i>
- CASTILLO: <i>No.</i>

32:37.415 --> 32:39.095
That's how you appeal
to the working class.

32:39.292 --> 32:41.612
<i>It's fantasy. As if, you know,
you're giving them a future.</i>

32:41.836 --> 32:42.836
Oh.

32:42.962 --> 32:44.756
- What the hell was that?
- Was that Marco?

32:45.006 --> 32:46.341
<i>Holy shit. Marco!</i>

32:46.591 --> 32:48.259
BEN: Marco, no! No, no, no, Marco!

32:48.468 --> 32:50.511
BUCKLEY: Marco! Oh, my God! Shit!

32:51.929 --> 32:55.683
It's like he killed himself
rather than be in one of our commercials.

32:57.185 --> 32:58.436
NELL: <i>Poor thing.</i>

32:59.687 --> 33:01.147
(IN SPANISH) We are rich in petroleum.
We have lithium.

33:01.439 --> 33:02.879
(SPEAKING ENGLISH) Uh-huh. Yes. Yes.

33:03.024 --> 33:04.651
We have compressed natural gas.

33:05.026 --> 33:08.363
<i>What I'm saying is,
Bolivia is an immensely rich country.</i>

33:08.613 --> 33:10.198
BEN: Trying out the crisis
message in the polls, sir,

33:10.448 --> 33:12.575
there are a lot of people who are saying

33:12.784 --> 33:16.120
that you are the only one
who understands how bad things are.

33:16.454 --> 33:17.747
The message is working.

33:17.955 --> 33:20.208
Or, at least, it's stopping the free fall.

33:20.458 --> 33:22.418
So I say, now we bet the house on it.

33:22.627 --> 33:25.171
We say it on the stump,
we say it in our spots,

33:25.380 --> 33:26.756
we say it to the press.

33:26.964 --> 33:29.342
We own crisis.

33:30.385 --> 33:31.386
Crisis.

33:31.636 --> 33:33.346
Now, what do you think, Ms. Bodine?

33:34.138 --> 33:36.307
Uh, I think you won't win.

33:36.557 --> 33:37.558
What?

33:37.809 --> 33:40.269
I think you're lookin' at
mid-20s. Not enough to win.

33:40.478 --> 33:41.854
You're gonna have to make
everyone else lose.

33:42.063 --> 33:44.065
That is, keeping them under 24%.

33:44.315 --> 33:45.316
You gotta go negative.

33:45.525 --> 33:48.485
No. No, no. In the last campaign,
we used attack ads, and it hurt us badly.

33:48.653 --> 33:50.988
And that is why I brought my oppo out.

33:51.322 --> 33:52.322
Sarah LeBlanc.

33:52.490 --> 33:55.368
Nobody asked you to do that.
We already have our own team.

33:55.576 --> 33:57.870
Oh, not like LeBlanc. She's the best.

33:58.079 --> 34:01.499
No offense, Jane, but if she's the best,
how come I've never heard of her?

34:01.708 --> 34:03.876
Uh, maybe because she's the best.

34:04.210 --> 34:05.586
And who is this people's person?

34:05.837 --> 34:10.049
That person is someone who can do as much,
or as little, as needed.

34:10.257 --> 34:12.635
Listen, Ms. Bodine,
I know what it's like in America.

34:12.844 --> 34:14.011
<i>I know what you guys do.</i>

34:14.219 --> 34:15.221
But here in Bolivia,

34:15.429 --> 34:18.014
the people do not like
negative campaigns. If we...

34:18.224 --> 34:19.434
Ben?

34:19.684 --> 34:21.853
Sir, negative ads move the numbers.

34:22.061 --> 34:24.021
But it's like settin' off a bomb.

34:24.230 --> 34:25.606
You'll take votes from Rivera,

34:25.857 --> 34:27.734
but you have no idea
where those votes'll go.

34:29.860 --> 34:32.029
Let your friend see what she can find.

34:32.739 --> 34:34.114
- Okay. Will do.
- (EXHALES)

34:35.408 --> 34:38.168
Oh, and I'd also like for her to do
a vulnerability study on you, sir.

34:38.202 --> 34:39.245
I've already been through that.

34:39.454 --> 34:40.538
Not with LeBlanc you haven't, sir.

34:40.746 --> 34:42.831
You've been doing so badly,
no one's been looking too hard.

34:43.040 --> 34:45.001
But if you start doing better,
the press will start digging.

34:45.208 --> 34:46.960
And last-minute surprises will kill.

34:47.210 --> 34:49.422
I'm not going to pay someone
to investigate me.

34:49.630 --> 34:52.049
I already know about me.
There's nothing to find out.

34:52.300 --> 34:53.885
Oh, there's always something
to find out, sir.

34:54.092 --> 34:55.386
And that's final.

34:56.219 --> 34:58.890
Okay. You are the boss.

35:05.897 --> 35:07.064
Do him first.

35:07.565 --> 35:10.234
BEN: <i>If I can finish this,
if you look at this last graph,</i>

35:10.443 --> 35:11.569
<i>it shows the three polls...</i>

35:11.778 --> 35:13.446
Listen up, everybody.

35:13.654 --> 35:15.406
Can I have your attention, please?

35:15.615 --> 35:16.866
<i>Everybody!</i>

35:17.074 --> 35:18.201
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

35:18.409 --> 35:19.744
- What'd you just say?
- Listen to you.

35:19.952 --> 35:21.579
Everyone, we're... Oh.

35:23.748 --> 35:24.874
(CLATTERS)

35:25.082 --> 35:26.793
We are gonna do something to Rivera

35:27.001 --> 35:29.462
that no politician wants
to have done to them.

35:29.670 --> 35:31.547
We are going to define him.

35:31.756 --> 35:33.633
The attack line is that he's a crook,

35:33.841 --> 35:36.302
he's corrupt, he's inexperienced,

35:36.511 --> 35:38.054
and he lies.

35:38.262 --> 35:40.932
Every day, we are
going to ring the big feet,

35:41.140 --> 35:43.059
<i>El Diario, La Razón, La Prensa,</i>

35:43.267 --> 35:46.187
and we are going to spoon-feed
them their Rivera story.

35:46.437 --> 35:48.437
We're gonna go through
every quote he's ever given,

35:48.606 --> 35:50.726
every person he's ever met,
every vote he's ever made,

35:50.817 --> 35:53.861
and we are gonna look for
ways of using it against him.

35:54.111 --> 35:56.111
- Eddie! Where's Eddie? Eddie!
- (SPEAKING SPANISH)

35:56.948 --> 35:58.741
Where are you? There you are.
You're my tracker. Okay?

35:58.950 --> 36:02.370
Every event that Rivera attends,
every speech, you tape it.

36:02.620 --> 36:05.623
If security beats you up,
you are doing your job right.

36:05.832 --> 36:07.250
And get that beating on tape.

36:07.458 --> 36:09.877
And if anyone has any qualms about this,

36:10.127 --> 36:12.213
thinks it's wrong in some way,

36:12.463 --> 36:14.006
you come and talk to me, okay?

36:14.215 --> 36:15.925
I will rent you a nice set of balls.

36:16.133 --> 36:18.344
Because there's only one wrong in this.

36:18.553 --> 36:20.888
Only one, and that is losing.

36:21.180 --> 36:24.809
There's only one wrong, losing.

36:30.815 --> 36:33.693
(WHISPERING) Maybe check
and see if anyone understood that.

36:34.151 --> 36:36.351
(SPEAKING SPANISH)
Raise your hand if you speak English.

36:39.073 --> 36:42.076
Now tell them to tell the people
that didn't understand what I just said.

36:42.869 --> 36:44.787
Explain it to the others, please.

36:44.996 --> 36:47.540
<i>Gracias. Gracias.</i>

36:49.125 --> 36:50.925
- (CROWD CHEERING)
- (RIVERA SPEAKING SPANISH)

37:05.349 --> 37:07.560
My God, his hair. It is amazing.

37:07.768 --> 37:09.937
(STAMMERS) Look, it doesn't move.

37:10.146 --> 37:11.146
(BEN CHUCKLES)

37:11.314 --> 37:12.607
- Close-up.
- Yeah.

37:12.815 --> 37:14.442
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

37:18.279 --> 37:19.655
No, no, no, no, that's great.
Keep diggin'.

37:19.864 --> 37:22.491
It's in there. All these guys
have something to hide.

37:22.700 --> 37:23.951
<i>I'm sure he's had an affair.</i>

37:24.160 --> 37:25.411
LEBLANC: I don't know about him,
but Castillo did.

37:25.620 --> 37:26.829
JANE: <i>Well, then let's use that, okay?</i>

37:27.038 --> 37:29.198
<i>But don't make it from us.
It can't be connected to us.</i>

37:29.332 --> 37:31.083
<i>Make it a grassroots something or other.</i>

37:31.292 --> 37:34.128
Castillo affair?

37:35.379 --> 37:36.631
(GUARD SPEAKING SPANISH)

37:36.839 --> 37:38.424
(CONVERSING IN SPANISH)

37:41.302 --> 37:43.012
CROWD: (CHANTING) Rivera! Rivera!

37:44.639 --> 37:45.973
Two years ago, Rivera's office

37:46.182 --> 37:50.019
purchased 27 Ford Explorers
for official use by the district.

37:50.227 --> 37:51.729
Sales price was 35K each.

37:51.938 --> 37:53.981
These are photocopies of
the actual receipts.

37:54.190 --> 37:55.608
They claimed 40,000 each.

37:55.816 --> 38:00.071
That is $135,000 of taxpayers' money

38:00.279 --> 38:01.906
going into someone's pocket.

38:02.114 --> 38:04.575
Bad, bad boy. You actually are a crook.

38:05.284 --> 38:06.327
- Synchronicity.
- LEBLANC: Mmm-hmm.

38:06.535 --> 38:08.704
It'd be great if we got shots
of his people driving these things,

38:08.913 --> 38:10.998
picking up their groceries
or pickin' up hookers or something.

38:11.207 --> 38:13.209
Wait. Where did you get these receipts?

38:13.417 --> 38:14.577
It's a black box op, Buckley.

38:14.627 --> 38:17.505
- (CELL PHONE CHIMING)
- Scooch. Scooch, scooch.

38:19.256 --> 38:20.576
NELL: <i>Page after page after page.</i>

38:20.758 --> 38:23.010
LEBLANC: <i>Yeah.
All the documentation is there.</i>

38:23.219 --> 38:24.553
NELL: <i>Did you see it? Here, look at these.</i>

38:24.762 --> 38:25.805
CANDY: (ON PHONE) <i>So about now,</i>

38:26.013 --> 38:28.265
<i>I imagine you've decided
that your horse can't win.</i>

38:28.474 --> 38:29.714
You brought in that little waif

38:29.809 --> 38:32.311
of a high school valedictorian
to do all your work for ya.

38:32.520 --> 38:35.481
<i>And now you're getting ready
to smear shit all over us.</i>

38:35.690 --> 38:36.983
Switch your TV on, sweetheart.

38:37.191 --> 38:38.751
(WHISPERS) Hey! Someone turn on the TV.

38:38.818 --> 38:41.612
(STAMMERS) What's wrong
with you? What happened?

38:42.989 --> 38:44.031
NELL: Oh, God.

38:44.532 --> 38:46.617
CANDY: <i>Twin boys.
I've seen 'em. Just adorable.</i>

38:46.993 --> 38:49.412
<i>I mean, if you're into
little pink bags of shit.</i>

38:49.620 --> 38:51.205
<i>But you know what I always say,</i>

38:51.414 --> 38:53.499
<i>children are a blessing from God,</i>

38:53.708 --> 38:55.668
<i>and Rivera has been doubly blessed.</i>

38:55.876 --> 39:00.047
<i>Children are a blessing from God,
and I have been doubly blessed.</i>

39:00.256 --> 39:01.257
LEBLANC: <i>So full of shit.</i>

39:01.465 --> 39:03.759
<i>A father wants his children
to be proud of him.</i>

39:03.968 --> 39:08.472
<i>That's why I promise the Bolivian people
that I will run a positive campaign.</i>

39:08.681 --> 39:09.681
Of course.

39:10.057 --> 39:11.183
What's the urgency?

39:11.392 --> 39:12.852
JANE: <i>It's the oldest trick
in the book, sir.</i>

39:13.060 --> 39:14.895
It's Candy's work again. They know
we have a shot if we go negative.

39:15.104 --> 39:16.147
They're just trying to block us.

39:16.355 --> 39:17.565
You are not the one out here, Ms. Bodine.

39:17.773 --> 39:19.608
If we go negative now,
we're going to get the Senator lynched.

39:19.817 --> 39:21.068
JANE: "He who is not courageous enough

39:21.277 --> 39:23.362
"to take risks will accomplish
nothing in life."

39:23.571 --> 39:25.489
Oh, look. Come on,
we don't wanna hear any more Sun Tzu.

39:25.698 --> 39:27.199
It is not Sun Tzu. It's Muhammad Ali.

39:27.408 --> 39:30.119
Sir, if you wanna win,
we're gonna have to take risks.

39:30.327 --> 39:31.912
We're gonna have to slash and burn.

39:32.121 --> 39:34.957
If you do not go negative, you do not win.

39:35.833 --> 39:37.251
Hugo is right.

39:37.460 --> 39:38.502
We don't go negative.

39:39.545 --> 39:40.963
I've made my decision.

39:44.759 --> 39:46.260
- Hey, Jane, one more thing.
- What?

39:46.469 --> 39:47.720
I think I might have something.

39:47.928 --> 39:49.805
Rivera was in the army when he was young.

39:50.014 --> 39:52.974
There's a newspaper article that
references a photograph of him in uniform.

39:53.059 --> 39:55.561
I could try and track it down if you think
there might be something there.

39:55.770 --> 39:56.771
Never mind Rivera.

39:56.979 --> 39:59.065
Give me everything you have
on Castillo, okay?

39:59.273 --> 40:00.441
